Also participating are Charlene Fernandez, Arizona House Minority Leader, Senator Andrea Dalessandro, Superior Mayor Mila Besich, and Andrea Martinez, CPLC Vice President Early Childhood Development.

post_text: The Chicanos Por La Causa - CPLC familia mourns the passing of Dr. Luis Aranda. He was a mentor to many Arizona State University students and helped in the founding of ASU's Hispanic Business Students Association. Dr. Aranda received his Bachelors of Music and Masters of Education degrees from the University of Arizona. He received his Juris Doctorate from the College of Law at Arizona State University where he was on the faculty of the W. P. Carey School of Business - ASU since 1975 and was a Professor Emeritus. We extend our heartfelt condolences to his family and friends.

post_text:
As part of Fry's Food Stores ongoing commitment to end hunger in Arizona communities, the company made a $20,000 donation to help sustain the Chicanos Por La Causa - CPLC Community Center food pantry in Phoenix as part of its Zero Hunger|Zero Waste social impact plan.

The CPLC Community Center serves as an educational facility for both adults and youth in the high needs area of the Carl Hayden neighborhood, with approximately over 90% of their youth participants coming from households that make less than $30,000 annually. The recent donation made by Fry‚Äôs helped the center almost double the amount of families receiving food, with the center now feeding more than 200 families per month. We thank our friends at Fry's Food Stores for their support and generosity.
text:
As part of Fry's Food Stores ongoing commitment to end hunger in Arizona communities, the company made a $20,000 donation to help sustain the Chicanos Por La Causa - CPLC Community Center food pantry in Phoenix as part of its Zero Hunger|Zero Waste social impact plan.

The recent donation made by Fry‚Äôs helped the center almost double the amount of families receiving food, with the center now feeding more than 200 families per month. We thank our friends at Fry's Food Stores for their support and generosity.

post_text: Small businesses are hurting. You know that, we know that. Chicanos Por La Causa - CPLC heard from you that Arizona small businesses were unfairly shut out of the initial round of federally backed loans intended to keep them operating and employees earning a paycheck. We applied to the Maricopa County IDA for $10 million in capital that, with an average loan of $65,000 each, would have supported up to 154 local businesses. It was a valid request with ample justification. But like a small business going to a big bank, our request was ignored. READ MORE: https://cplc.org/blog/viewpost.php?id=1065

post_text:
For a couple of years now, Centro de la Familia and Tiempo have volunteered to distribute food boxes to the community every two weeks on Wednesday at the Maryvale Center. This food pantry has served over 200 families every time a distribution day is held.

Instead of canceling the food pantry, last week, as a result of Covid19. The team, using precautionary measures for the safety of staff and clients, turned the distribution into a drive-thru for added safety and provided over 200 food boxes.

CPLC could not do this without our partnership with St. Mary‚Äôs Food Bank who supplies all of the food.

post_text:
CPLC Statement on Immigration Issues:

"Within the many challenges facing Arizona today are ample opportunities pertaining to education, economic development and new avenues for equity. Punitive laws on immigration ‚Äì such as a proposed statewide ban on sanctuary cities ‚Äì are as unnecessary as they are detrimental, with Chicanos Por La Causa believing our state‚Äôs focus and energy would be much better spent on pragmatic public policy than polarizing politics. Arizona has made real progress over the last 10 years since SB 1070, and any effort to further divide Arizona voters on such emotive issues only serves a giant setback in reliving the past. Time and energy among elected officials and community leaders would be better invested by working together toward sensible solutions that build a stronger future for Arizona, one we can all be proud to call home. We should take full advantage of such an opportunity, not squander it."

post_text:
"Human progress is neither automatic nor inevitable. Even a superficial look at history reveals that no social advance rolls in on the wheels inevitability. Every step towards the goal of justice requires sacrifice, suffering, and struggle; the tireless exertions and passionate concern of dedicated individuals.

"Without persistent effort, time itself becomes an ally of the insurgent and primitive forces of irrational emotionalism and social destruction. This is no time for apathy or complacency. This is a time for vigorous and positive action."

CPLC De Colores is holding a coat drive! Survivors of domestic violence often arrive at our shelter with few personal belongings. With cold weather approaching, residents are in need of warm winter coats for women, men, and children of all ages.

New or gently used jackets and coats will be accepted Monday through Friday, 9am to 4pm at the following locations:

CPLC Corporate Office
1112 E Buckeye Road

post_text: Responding to a loved one who has disclosed intimate partner violence is never an easy experience. One may feel angry, sad, overwhelmed, helpless, or vengeful. However, the most important way to respond to a friend is to listen without judgment, maintain confidentiality, validate their experience, convey belief, and remind them that they have options. ‚ÄúI believe you.‚Äù ‚ÄúIt wasn‚Äôt your fault.‚Äù ‚ÄúYou didn‚Äôt deserve this.‚Äù These are all statements you can make when a friend or loved one discloses their experience of abuse. #BelieveSurvivors #EndDVinAZ

post_text: What keeps you up at night? Leading a 50-year-old organization is a responsibility that David Adame doesn‚Äôt take lightly. He is the son of a working-class veteran and grandson of Mexican immigrants who is now leading one of the largest Latino community development corporations in the United States ‚Äî headquartered in the same neighborhood he grew up in. He shares on Arizona Achievers how he empowers a family of nearly 1,000 employees at Chicanos Por La Causa (CPLC) that impact the lives of 380,000 annually by delivering 48+ programs and services in three US states and exploring expansion into Texas, California and Mexico. The interview will be available soon on The Social Television Network (stnTV). #leadership #communityempowerment #cplc50 #nonprofitleadership #topceos #latinoleaders

It was at that moment that Mercado Chavez saw an opportunity to teach her kids, and the many children she works with at the Chicanos Por La Causa Headstart Center in Somerton about the origin of their food.

That‚Äôs exactly what happened next, with a couple of dollars and with the generous donations of various community members, the Farm to School garden is going on to its third year of existence.

post_text:
The senseless shootings that occurred this weekend are a brutal reminder of the progress we have yet to make as a nation.

The shooter in El Paso, a professed racist, intentionally targeted people of Mexican descent. This strikes us personally. These victims could just have easily been any of us, our children, our friends, our family.

This act of terrorism is sadly not isolated. It is the latest in a string of mass shootings targeting various groups‚Äîchildren, Muslim, Jewish, Black.

Unfortunately, our leaders in Washington, DC are only fanning the flames of violence. Our leadership in congress has continually obstructed any meaningful reform in gun laws. And the racist and xenophobic rhetoric from the White House only encourages such tragedy.

As mass shootings seem to occur more and more frequently, the natural reaction may be to disconnect and disengage. We urge you to lean in.

We must connect with our community and engage politically to elect leaders who condemn such violence and intolerance through consistent action rather than empty words.

Unfortunately, our leaders in Washington, DC are only fanning the flames of violence. Our leadership in congress has continually obstructed any meaningful reform in gun laws. And the racist and xenophobic rhetoric from the White House only encourages such tragedy.

As mass shootings seem to occur more and more frequently, the natural reaction may be to disconnect and disengage. We urge you to lean in.

post_text: Congratulations Chicanos Por La Causa President & CEO David Adame for receiving The Honoris Causa Doctoral Council‚Äôs highest degree of Honorary Doctorate. This special conferral occurred on Thursday, July 25th at the AAPAUNAM auditorium, the National Autonomous University of Mexico (UNAM). Awarded in recognition of David‚Äôs wide-ranging work in promoting education, culture, and social responsibility, this prestigious doctorate is recognized by noteworthy universities and educational institutions across Mexico. David graduated with 17 fellow Honoris Causa Doctors in the generation of Luis Wertman Zazlav. The Honoris Causa is given based on a life trajectory. The theme of this Doctorate is the work done empowering the Mexican and Mexican American communities in Education, Culture, and Social Responsibility.

Arizona-- tune in to Arizona PBS this Sunday to see the CPLC Documentary, "Dime Quien Eres!" This documentary will tell the story of Arizona's Chicano movement and CPLC's role in the development of our community.

For viewers in Tucson or otherwise outside of broadcast area, you can view the film online at www.cplc.org/doc

post_text: Thank you to all volunteers who participated to help out the residents of our senior housing communities! Volunteers cleaned apartments and assisted with the tasks that many seniors are no longer able to do themselves. Thanks especially to employees of Synchrony, Banner Health, Bank of America, Wells Fargo, Blue Cross Blue Shield of Arizona, Salt River Project, and Adult Protective Services for your efforts!

post_text:
Arizona-- check out the CPLC documentary airing this weekend on PBS!

Arizona PBS presents "Chicanos Por La Causa: Dime Quien Eres," a documentary film on the story of CPLC and the rise of the Arizona Chicano movement. The film will be available on PBS stations statewide except in the Tucson area.

Tune in this weekend:
Sunday, June 16th
5:00pm

Watch the teaser trailer at: https://cplc.org/blog/viewpost.php?id=29
